  \begin {tikzcd}
    C\ar [r, dashed, "\exists !"', "\hat {F}"] & E \\
    C\ar [u, "y"]\ar [ur, "F"']
  \end {tikzcd}


 commutes. This functor is called the Yoneda extension of F.

It remains to show that \hat {F} is cocontinuous. To do so, it suffices
  to show it is a left adjoint. We define the functor E\xrightarrow {R}   \hat {C} by Re = E(F-, e). To exhibit the adjunction, compute for
  P\in \hat {C} and e\in  E,      \begin {aligned}       \hat {C}(P, Re) &\cong  \hat {C}(\operatorname *{colim}_{(c,x)\in \text {el}(P)}C(-, c), Re) &&\text {by the density formula} \\       &\cong  \operatorname *{lim}_{(c, x)\in \text {el}(P)^\text {op}} \hat {C}(C(-, c), Re) &&\text {by the       representability of colimits} \\       &\cong  \operatorname *{lim}_{(c, x)\in \text {el}(P)^\text {op}} (Re)c &&\text {by the Yoneda lemma} \\       &\cong  \operatorname *{lim}_{(c, x)\in \text {el}(P)^\text {op}} E(Fc, e) &&\text {by definition of } R \\       &\cong  E(\operatorname *{colim}_{(c, x)\in \text {el}(P)} Fc, e) &&\text {by the representability of colimits} \\       &\cong  E(\hat {F}P, e) &&\text {by definition of } \hat {F}.     \end {aligned}

To demonstrate naturality, we need to show that for any map y\xrightarrow {f} x
  in C, the diagram 




